const RAW_MARKDOWN = "# Classification of Elements and Periodicity in Properties\n\n## Complete Rewritten Question Bank\n\n**Structure:** All questions are presented first. The consolidated answer key follows the complete question set, and the worked solutions appear after the answer key.\n\n---\n\n# Part I \u2014 Questions\n\n## Section 2.1 \u2014 Integer / Numerical-Answer Type Questions (22)\n\nQ1. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 4s electron of Ca (Z = 20). [If your answer is 2.85, write 0285]\n\nQ2. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of Fe (Z = 26).\n\nQ3. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of Br (Z = 35).\n\nQ4. The successive ionisation energies of an element (in eV) are: $IE_1=9.5,\\ IE_2=18.2,\\ IE_3=27.5,\\ IE_4=120.0,\\ IE_5=155.0$. What is the stable oxidation state of this element?\n\nQ5. Using the standard $\\Delta_{eg}H$ data table, find the total number of elements up to atomic number 20 (inclusive) that have a positive (endothermic) first electron gain enthalpy.\n\nQ6. In a hypothetical universe, each orbital can hold a maximum of 3 electrons instead of 2, but every other filling rule (Aufbau order, subshell types, etc.) stays the same. Find the number of elements that would occupy the block filled by the 4s, 3d and 4p subshells (i.e. \"period 4\") in this universe.\n\nQ7. The covalent radius of phosphorus is 1.10 \u00c5. Using Slater's rule to find $Z_{eff}$ of its 3p electron, calculate the electronegativity of P on the Allred\u2013Rochow scale. (Report your answer \u00d7 100, to the nearest integer.)\n\nQ8. For an atom, $IE = 14.0$ eV and $EA = 2.8$ eV. Calculate its electronegativity on the Pauling scale using the Mulliken relation and the conversion $\\chi_P=\\chi_M/2.8$. (Report \u00d710.)\n\nQ9. Bond dissociation energies: $E_{A-A}=44$, $E_{B-B}=64$, $E_{A-B}=72$ kcal/mol. If $\\chi_A = 3.50$, use the Pauling relation to calculate $\\chi_B$. (Report \u00d7100, nearest integer.)\n\nQ10. Two elements have electronegativities $\\chi_A=1.2$ and $\\chi_B=3.2$. Using the Hannay\u2013Smith formula, calculate the % ionic character of the A\u2013B bond.\n\nQ11. A free 3d-block $M^{3+}$ ion has a spin-only magnetic moment of 4.90 BM. How many unpaired electrons does it have?\n\nQ12. $2\\times10^{6}$ gaseous bromine atoms release a total of $9.6\\times10^{-13}$ J of energy on converting to $\\text{Br}^-$ ions. Calculate the electron affinity of Br in eV/atom.\n\nQ13. Given: $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^+)=-6x$ (i.e. $IE_1=6x$), $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^{2+})=-9x$ (i.e. $IE_2=9x$), $\\Delta H_{IE}(A^{2+})=14x$ (i.e. $IE_3=14x$), $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^{4+})=-20x$ (i.e. $IE_4=20x$), $\\Delta H_{IE}(A^{4+})=26x$ (i.e. $IE_5=26x$). If $\\Delta H$ for $A^+(g)\\to A^{5+}(g)$ is $ax$, find $a$.\n\nQ14. For formation of $MX_3(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-900$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta H_{sub}(M)=150$ kJ/mol, bond-dissociation energy for $\\tfrac32X_2\\to3X(g)=300$ kJ/mol, $IE_1+IE_2+IE_3(M)=1200$ kJ/mol, lattice enthalpy of formation $=-1350$ kJ/mol. If $q$ is the electron gain enthalpy of $X$ (per atom, in kJ/mol), calculate $q/50$.\n\nQ15. Heat of solution of $AB(s)$ is $+0.55\\times10^{x}$ kcal/mol. Lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of $AB(s)=780$ kcal/mol, hydration enthalpy of $A^+(g)=-430$ kcal/mol, hydration enthalpy of $B^-(g)=-295$ kcal/mol. Find $x$.\n\nQ16. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 4s electron of K (Z=19) and $Z_{eff}$ for the 2p electron of N (Z=7). Report $\\left|Z_{eff}(\\text{N})-Z_{eff}(\\text{K})\\right|\\times100$.\n\nQ17. (Simplified model \u2014 assume EN is directly proportional to %s-character.) If the electronegativity of $sp^3$ carbon is 2.50, calculate the electronegativity of $sp$ carbon under this proportionality. (Report \u00d710.)\n\nQ18. In an isoelectronic pair, a cation has $Z_{eff}=15$ and ionic radius 80 pm; the corresponding anion has radius 200 pm. Using $r_{cation}/r_{anion}=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/Z_{eff}(\\text{cation})$, calculate $Z_{eff}$ of the anion. Report $Z_{eff}\\times10$.\n\nQ19. Find the total number of species with exactly 3 unpaired electrons (free ion, high-spin) among: $\\text{Cr}^{3+}, \\text{Mn}^{2+}, \\text{Fe}^{3+}, \\text{Co}^{2+}, \\text{Ni}^{2+}, \\text{V}^{2+}$.\n\nQ20. Find the total number of diamagnetic species among: $\\text{Zn}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}, \\text{Cu}^{+}, \\text{Fe}^{2+}, \\text{Mn}^{7+}$.\n\nQ21. Find the number of p-block elements among the atomic numbers: 31, 47, 56, 82, 36, 92, 15.\n\nQ22. Calculate the total number of electrons present in all the d-subshells of a neutral Ag atom (Z = 47).\n\n## Section 2.2 \u2014 Multiple-Choice Questions: Single Correct (15)\n\nQ1. The correct increasing order of first ionisation enthalpy is:\n\n   (a) B < Be < C < N\n\n   (b) Be < B < C < N\n\n   (c) B < C < Be < N\n\n   (d) C < B < Be < N\n\nQ2. Select the correct order of atomic radius in the boron family:\n\n   (a) Al < Ga < In < Tl\n\n   (b) Ga < Al < In < Tl\n\n   (c) Al < In < Ga < Tl\n\n   (d) Tl < In < Ga < Al\n\nQ3. Which of the following is not a transition element by the strict definition (incomplete d-subshell in atom or common ion)?\n\n   (a) Fe\n\n   (b) Zn\n\n   (c) Mn\n\n   (d) Cr\n\nQ4. Nearly identical atomic radii due to lanthanide contraction is best shown by the pair:\n\n   (a) Sc, Y\n\n   (b) Zr, Hf\n\n   (c) Ti, Zr\n\n   (d) Fe, Ru\n\nQ5. The correct order of electron gain enthalpy (magnitude) for halogens is:\n\n   (a) F > Cl > Br > I\n\n   (b) Cl > F > Br > I\n\n   (c) Cl > Br > F > I\n\n   (d) Br > Cl > F > I\n\nQ6. The correct order of electronegativity for carbon in different hybridisation states is:\n\n   (a) $sp^3 > sp^2 > sp$\n\n   (b) $sp > sp^2 > sp^3$\n\n   (c) $sp^2 > sp > sp^3$\n\n   (d) $sp^3 > sp > sp^2$\n\nQ7. Which of the following oxides is amphoteric?\n\n   (a) Na\u2082O\n\n   (b) SO\u2083\n\n   (c) Al\u2082O\u2083\n\n   (d) Cl\u2082O\u2087\n\nQ8. Among the isoelectronic species F\u207b, Na\u207a, Mg\u00b2\u207a, O\u00b2\u207b, the one with the smallest ionic radius is:\n\n   (a) F\u207b\n\n   (b) O\u00b2\u207b\n\n   (c) Na\u207a\n\n   (d) Mg\u00b2\u207a\n\nQ9. Which statement correctly reflects the inert-pair effect?\n\n   (a) Pb(IV) is more stable than Pb(II)\n\n   (b) Tl(I) is more stable than Tl(III)\n\n   (c) Bi(V) is more stable than Bi(III)\n\n   (d) Sn(II) is less stable than Sn(IV)\n\nQ10. The correct order of hydracid strength (aqueous) is:\n\n   (a) HF > HCl > HBr > HI\n\n   (b) HI > HBr > HCl > HF\n\n   (c) HCl > HF > HBr > HI\n\n   (d) HBr > HI > HCl > HF\n\nQ11. The second electron gain enthalpy of oxygen ($\\text{O}^-\\to\\text{O}^{2-}$) is:\n\n   (a) always negative\n\n   (b) always positive\n\n   (c) zero\n\n   (d) element-independent\n\nQ12. By Fajans' rules, which pair correctly predicts greater covalent character?\n\n   (a) BeCl\u2082 more covalent than MgCl\u2082\n\n   (b) MgCl\u2082 more covalent than BeCl\u2082\n\n   (c) CaCl\u2082 more covalent than BeCl\u2082\n\n   (d) BeCl\u2082 and CaCl\u2082 equally covalent\n\nQ13. Which of the following is classified as a metalloid?\n\n   (a) Se\n\n   (b) Sb\n\n   (c) Sn\n\n   (d) Bi\n\nQ14. An element shows a huge jump between $IE_1$ and $IE_2$ (i.e. $IE_2\\gg IE_1$), with no comparable jump afterward for several removals. This element most likely belongs to group:\n\n   (a) 1\n\n   (b) 2\n\n   (c) 13\n\n   (d) 14\n\nQ15. The correct order of lattice enthalpy (magnitude) is:\n\n   (a) LiCl > NaCl > KCl > RbCl\n\n   (b) NaCl > LiCl > KCl > RbCl\n\n   (c) RbCl > KCl > NaCl > LiCl\n\n   (d) KCl > NaCl > LiCl > RbCl\n\n## Section 2.3 \u2014 Correct-Order Code-Number Questions (6)\n\nInstructions (Use the code-number convention below): each row states an order and a property. Some rows are correct, some are deliberately wrong. Add up the code numbers as instructed.\n\n### CO-1\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Al}^{3+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}<\\text{Na}^+$ | Ionic radius | 05 |\n| 2 | $\\text{F}^-<\\text{Cl}^-<\\text{Br}^-<\\text{I}^-$ | Ionic radius | 12 |\n| 3 | $\\text{N}^{3-}<\\text{O}^{2-}<\\text{F}^-$ | Ionic radius | 07 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Fe}^{2+}>\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ | Ionic radius | 03 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Li}^+<\\text{Na}^+<\\text{K}^+<\\text{Rb}^+$ | Magnitude of hydration enthalpy | 14 |\n\n(Example: if only rows 2 and 4 are correct, the answer is $12+03=15$.)\n\n### CO-2\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Be}>\\text{B}$ | First IE | 06 |\n| 2 | $\\text{N}>\\text{O}$ | First IE | 09 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Cl}>\\text{F}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 04 |\n| 4 | $\\text{S}>\\text{Se}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 11 |\n| 5 | $\\text{F}>\\text{Cl}$ | Electronegativity | 02 |\n| 6 | $\\text{S}<\\text{O}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 15 |\n\n### CO-3\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Zr}\\approx\\text{Hf}$ | Atomic radius | 07 |\n| 2 | $\\text{Sc}<\\text{Y}<\\text{La}$ | Atomic radius | 13 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Cu}>\\text{Zn}$ | Atomic radius (3d) | 09 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Eu}>\\text{Sm}$ | Atomic radius (lanthanoids) | 05 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Ce}^{4+}<\\text{Ce}^{3+}$ | Ionic radius | 18 |\n| 6 | $\\text{La}>\\text{Lu}$ | Atomic radius | 10 |\n\n### CO-4\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}<\\text{MgO}<\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{SiO}_2$ | Acidic character | 17 |\n| 2 | $\\text{Mn}_2\\text{O}_7>\\text{MnO}_2$ | Acidic character | 04 |\n| 3 | $\\text{HF}<\\text{HCl}<\\text{HBr}<\\text{HI}$ | Acid strength (aqueous) | 21 |\n| 4 | $\\text{NH}_3<\\text{PH}_3$ | Basicity | 08 |\n| 5 | $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4>\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_3$ | Acid strength | 12 |\n| 6 | $\\text{Bi(V)}>\\text{Bi(III)}$ | Thermodynamic stability | 19 |\n\n### CO-5\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $sp>sp^2>sp^3$ | EN of carbon | 03 |\n| 2 | $\\text{C}{\\equiv}\\text{C}>\\text{C}{=}\\text{C}>\\text{C}{-}\\text{C}$ | EN of carbon in the bond | 14 |\n| 3 | In $\\text{NF}_3$, bond polarises toward N | Bond polarity | 20 |\n| 4 | $\\text{O}^{2-}<\\text{O}^-<\\text{O}<\\text{O}^+$ | Electronegativity | 06 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Ga}>\\text{Al}$ | Electronegativity | 09 |\n| 6 | $\\text{Hg}>\\text{Cd}>\\text{Zn}$ | Electronegativity | 17 |\n\n### CO-6\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{LiF}>\\text{NaF}>\\text{KF}>\\text{RbF}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 22 |\n| 2 | $\\text{MgO}>\\text{NaCl}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 05 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Li}^+>\\text{Na}^+>\\text{K}^+$ | Magnitude of hydration enthalpy | 11 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Li}^+>\\text{Na}^+>\\text{K}^+$ | Ionic mobility in water | 16 |\n| 5 | $\\text{CsCl}>\\text{NaCl}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 08 |\n| 6 | $\\text{BaO}>\\text{CaO}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 13 |\n\n## Section 2.4 \u2014 Subjective / Long-Answer Problems (56)\n\nThe first 6 problems below form a compact \"core\" set; Q7\u2013Q56 (further below) extend this into a full 50-problem drill bank organised by topic.\n\nQ1. How many electrons in the $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ ion (Z = 26) have azimuthal quantum number $\\ell=1$ (i.e., are in p-orbitals)?\n\nQ2. The covalent radius of nitrogen is 0.70 \u00c5. Using Slater's rule to find $Z_{eff}$ of its 2p electron, calculate the electronegativity of N on the Allred\u2013Rochow scale.\n\nQ3. Heat of solution of a salt $AB(s)$ is $+15$ kcal/mol. Hydration enthalpy of $A^+(g)=-120$ kcal/mol and of $B^-(g)=-95$ kcal/mol. Calculate the lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of $AB(s)$.\n\nQ4. For the formation of $MX_2(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-650$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of $M=180$ kJ/mol; bond dissociation enthalpy of $X_2(g)\\to 2X(g)=190$ kJ/mol; $IE_1+IE_2$ of $M=1400$ kJ/mol; lattice enthalpy of formation $=-1300$ kJ/mol. Calculate the electron gain enthalpy of $X$ (per atom, in kJ/mol).\n\nQ5. For the formation of $AB(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-380$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of $A=90$ kJ/mol; bond dissociation enthalpy for $\\tfrac12B_2\\to B=120$ kJ/mol; $IE_1(A)=480$ kJ/mol; electron gain enthalpy of $B=-350$ kJ/mol. Calculate the lattice enthalpy of formation $U$, and report $-U/100$.\n\nQ6. Examine the following ten statements. Count how many are correct ($x$) and how many are incorrect ($y$), then report $|x-y|^2$.\n\n(i) $\\text{HF}>\\text{HCl}>\\text{HBr}>\\text{HI}$ \u2014 bond enthalpy\n\n(ii) $\\text{NH}_3>\\text{PH}_3>\\text{AsH}_3$ \u2014 bond angle\n\n(iii) $\\text{Li}^+<\\text{Na}^+<\\text{K}^+$ \u2014 ionic mobility in water\n\n(iv) $\\text{F}_2<\\text{Cl}_2<\\text{Br}_2<\\text{I}_2$ \u2014 bond dissociation enthalpy\n\n(v) $\\text{Sc}^{3+}<\\text{Ti}^{4+}$ \u2014 ionic radius\n\n(vi) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5>\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_3$ \u2014 acidic strength\n\n(vii) $\\text{Be}^{2+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}<\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ \u2014 |hydration enthalpy|\n\n(viii) $\\text{Cu}^{2+}<\\text{Cu}^+$ \u2014 stability in aqueous solution\n\n(ix) $\\text{I}^-<\\text{Br}^-<\\text{Cl}^-<\\text{F}^-$ \u2014 reducing power\n\n(x) $\\text{BeCl}_2<\\text{MgCl}_2<\\text{CaCl}_2$ \u2014 covalent character\n\n### Extended Subjective Problems (Q7-Q56)\n\n### Electronic Configuration & Magnetism (Q7\u2013Q11)\nQ7. How many electrons in the $\\text{Cu}$ atom (Z = 29, ground state) have azimuthal quantum number $\\ell=2$?\n\nQ8. Find the total number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of Cr (Z = 24), and hence its spin-only magnetic moment.\n\nQ9. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment of $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ (free ion).\n\nQ10. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment of $\\text{Ni}^{2+}$ (free ion).\n\nQ11. How many electrons in $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ (Z = 26) have principal quantum number $n=3$?\n\n### Zeff / Slater's Rules (Q12\u2013Q16)\nQ12. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of Se (Z = 34).\n\nQ13. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of Cu (Z = 29).\n\nQ14. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 3s electron of Mg (Z = 12).\n\nQ15. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3p electron of Ar (Z = 18).\n\nQ16. For Cu (Z = 29), calculate $Z_{eff}$ for its 3d electron and separately for its 4s electron, and report the difference. Explain in one line why this difference is chemically important.\n\n### Atomic & Ionic Radius (Q17\u2013Q21)\nQ17. In an isoelectronic pair, the cation has $Z_{eff}=18$ and radius 68 pm; the corresponding anion has radius 172 pm. Using $r_{cation}/r_{anion}=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/Z_{eff}(\\text{cation})$, estimate $Z_{eff}$ of the anion.\n\nQ18. Zr (Z = 40) and Hf (Z = 72) have nearly identical atomic radii (145 pm and 144 pm respectively) despite Hf lying a full period below Zr. Explain this using electronic configuration.\n\nQ19. Using the Schomaker\u2013Stevenson relation, estimate the A\u2013B bond length given $r_A=1.20$ \u00c5, $r_B=0.99$ \u00c5, and $\\Delta\\chi = 0.5$.\n\nQ20. Ionic radii: $\\text{Fe}=126$ pm, $\\text{Fe}^{2+}\\approx76$ pm, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}\\approx64$ pm. Explain this order in terms of $Z_{eff}$ per electron.\n\nQ21. Given approximate N\u2013N bond lengths: single (hydrazine-type) \u2248 145 pm, double (azo-type) \u2248 125 pm, triple (N\u2082) \u2248 110 pm \u2014 explain the trend using bond order and hybridisation.\n\n### Ionisation Enthalpy (Q22\u2013Q26)\nQ22. An element shows successive ionisation energies (eV): $IE_1=8.3,\\ IE_2=16.7,\\ IE_3=25.0,\\ IE_4=45.0,\\ IE_5=54.0$. Identify the likely group and stable oxidation state.\n\nQ23. Given $IE_1(\\text{Be})=900$ and $IE_1(\\text{B})=801$ kJ/mol, explain why Be's is higher despite B having one more proton.\n\nQ24. An element has $IE_1=737$, $IE_2=1450$, $IE_3=7732$, $IE_4=10539$ kJ/mol. Identify where the giant jump occurs and state the element's most probable valency.\n\nQ25. Using $E_n=-13.6Z^2/n^2$ eV, calculate the ionisation energy of $\\text{Li}^{2+}$ (a hydrogen-like species, Z = 3) from its ground state ($n=1$).\n\nQ26. Data: sublimation enthalpy of Li = 159 kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Li})=520$ kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of $\\text{Li}^+=-519$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of Cs = 76 kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Cs})=376$ kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of $\\text{Cs}^+=-263$ kJ/mol. Calculate the net energy change (sublimation + ionisation + hydration) for each metal converting to its aqueous cation, and use the result to explain why Li is the stronger reducing agent in water despite its higher gas-phase IE.\n\n### Electron Gain Enthalpy (Q27\u2013Q31)\nQ27. Given $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{F})=-328$ and $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{Cl})=-349$ kJ/mol, explain numerically (in terms of orbital size) why Cl's value is more negative despite F having higher $Z_{eff}$ and smaller size.\n\nQ28. $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{O})=-141$ kJ/mol but $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{O})$ (for $\\text{O}^-\\to\\text{O}^{2-}$) is strongly positive. Given that MgO nonetheless forms with a large negative overall lattice enthalpy of formation ($-3795$ kJ/mol) compensating, explain why $\\text{O}^{2-}$ is stable in the solid despite the unfavourable gas-phase second electron gain.\n\nQ29. $3\\times10^6$ gaseous chlorine atoms release a total of $1.68\\times10^{-12}$ J of energy on converting to $\\text{Cl}^-$ ions. Calculate the electron affinity of Cl in eV/atom.\n\nQ30. Using the NCERT-style data $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{N})=+31$ kJ/mol (unfavourable) and $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{P})=-72$ kJ/mol (favourable), explain this reversal using electron configuration.\n\nQ31. Explain, with reference to electron configuration, why $\\Delta_{eg}H_1$ of Ne (+116 kJ/mol) is more strongly positive than that of He (+48 kJ/mol), even though both are noble gases with closed shells.\n\n### Electronegativity (Q32\u2013Q39)\nQ32. Bond energies: $E_{A-A}=150$, $E_{B-B}=80$, $E_{A-B}=145$ kJ/mol. Given $\\chi_B=2.20$, calculate $\\chi_A$ using the Pauling relation ($\\Delta$ in kJ/mol, use $0.102\\sqrt\\Delta$).\n\nQ33. For chlorine, $IE=1140$ kJ/mol and $EA=349$ kJ/mol. Calculate the Mulliken electronegativity (in the kJ/mol-based formula $\\chi_M=(IE+EA)/(2\\times96.5)$) and convert it to the Pauling scale using $\\chi_P\\approx\\chi_M/2.8$.\n\nQ34. Estimate $\\chi_{AR}$ (Allred\u2013Rochow) for bromine given covalent radius $r=1.14$ \u00c5 and $Z_{eff}=7.60$ (from Slater's rules).\n\nQ35. Two elements have $\\chi_A=1.5$ and $\\chi_B=3.7$. Calculate the % ionic character of the A\u2013B bond using (a) the Hannay\u2013Smith formula and (b) Pauling's exponential formula. Compare the two estimates.\n\nQ36. Using $\\chi_{\\text{O}}=3.44$, $\\chi_{\\text{H}}=2.20$, and $\\chi_{\\text{K}}=0.82$, predict whether K\u2013O\u2013H behaves as an acid or a base, showing your comparison explicitly.\n\nQ37. Given that the electronegativity of $sp^3$-hybridised carbon is 2.50, and assuming EN is directly proportional to %s-character, calculate the electronegativity of $sp^2$-hybridised carbon. State which C\u2013H bond (in ethane, ethene, or ethyne) would be expected to be the most acidic, and why.\n\nQ38. Using the Schomaker\u2013Stevenson correction $d_{A-B}=r_A+r_B-9\\Delta\\chi$ (pm), calculate the C\u2013F bond length given $r_C=77$ pm, $r_F=64$ pm, and $\\chi_C=2.55,\\ \\chi_F=3.98$.\n\nQ39. The group electronegativity of $-\\text{CF}_3$ (\u22483.46) is much higher than that of $-\\text{CH}_3$ (\u22482.30). Using this, predict and justify which is a stronger acid: $\\text{CH}_3\\text{COOH}$ or $\\text{CF}_3\\text{COOH}$.\n\n### Chemical Periodicity (Q40\u2013Q44)\nQ40. $\\text{Tl}^{3+}$ is a stronger oxidising agent than $\\text{Pb}^{4+}$ is often assumed to be, yet both reflect the same underlying effect. Name the effect and explain why Tl(III) and Pb(IV) are both relatively oxidising compared to their lower-oxidation-state counterparts.\n\nQ41. Calculate the average oxidation state of sulfur in $\\text{S}_4\\text{O}_6^{2-}$ (tetrathionate ion), and explain why this average does not correspond to a single real oxidation state on every sulfur atom.\n\nQ42. Rank $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}$, $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$, and $\\text{SO}_3$ in order of increasing acidic character, justifying each placement using electronegativity/bonding-type reasoning.\n\nQ43. Explain, using two different mechanisms, why (a) $\\text{HI}$ is a stronger acid than $\\text{HF}$ in water, while (b) $\\text{HF}$ is a stronger acid than $\\text{CH}_4$'s C\u2013H bond. (Your explanation should show that these are governed by different factors.)\n\nQ44. Using Fajans' rules, predict which member of each pair has greater covalent character: (a) $\\text{MgCl}_2$ vs $\\text{CaCl}_2$; (b) $\\text{AgCl}$ vs $\\text{NaCl}$ (same approximate cation radius).\n\n### Lattice Enthalpy, Hydration & Born\u2013Haber (Q45\u2013Q51)\nQ45. For the formation of NaBr(s): $\\Delta H_f=-361.4$ kJ/mol, sublimation enthalpy of Na $=108.4$ kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Na})=495.8$ kJ/mol, $\\tfrac12D(\\text{Br}_2)=96.4$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Br})=-324.5$ kJ/mol. Calculate the lattice enthalpy of formation of NaBr(s).\n\nQ46. Using $|\\Delta H_{hyd}|\\propto z^2/r$, and given $r(\\text{Mg}^{2+})=72$ pm and $r(\\text{Ca}^{2+})=100$ pm (same charge $z=2$), calculate the ratio $|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Mg}^{2+})|:|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Ca}^{2+})|$.\n\nQ47. Lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of a salt $AB(s)=690$ kJ/mol; hydration enthalpy of $A^+=-380$ kJ/mol; hydration enthalpy of $B^-=-310$ kJ/mol. Calculate $\\Delta H_{sol}$ and comment on what this borderline value implies about the salt's solubility.\n\nQ48. Arrange $\\text{LiF}, \\text{NaF}, \\text{KF}, \\text{RbF}$ in decreasing order of lattice enthalpy magnitude, and separately arrange $\\text{NaF}, \\text{NaCl}, \\text{NaBr}, \\text{NaI}$ in decreasing order \u2014 explain why the two orders are controlled by different ions.\n\nQ49. Predict, using Fajans' rules, which is expected to have the higher melting point: $\\text{LiCl}$ or $\\text{CsCl}$. Justify using polarising power.\n\nQ50. $\\text{Li}^+$ has a smaller bare ionic radius than $\\text{Cs}^+$, yet $\\text{Li}^+$ has lower ionic mobility in water. Resolve this apparent contradiction.\n\nQ51. For the formation of $\\text{MCl}_2(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-796$ kJ/mol, sublimation enthalpy of M $=178$ kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{M})=590$ kJ/mol, $D(\\text{Cl}_2)=242$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Cl})=-349$ kJ/mol (\u00d72 for two Cl atoms), lattice enthalpy of formation $=-2258$ kJ/mol. Calculate $IE_2(\\text{M})$.\n\n### Mixed & Comprehensive (Q52\u2013Q56)\nQ52. An element X has: high $IE_1$, high electronegativity, small atomic radius, and forms an acidic, covalent oxide. Predict whether X is likely to be found in the upper-right or lower-left region of the periodic table, and list two properties you would expect for its hydride.\n\nQ53. Two unknown elements, P and Q, are in the same period. P has a lower $IE_1$ and lower electronegativity than Q. Predict, with reasoning, which one (a) has the larger atomic radius, (b) forms the more basic oxide, (c) is more likely to act as a reducing agent.\n\nQ54. An element M forms $\\text{MCl}_2$ that is highly ionic and water-soluble, but a related element M\u2032 (same group, smaller period number, similar charge) forms $\\text{M}'\\text{Cl}_2$ that is markedly more covalent and less soluble. Identify which of M/M\u2032 has the smaller cation, and explain using polarising power.\n\nQ55. Write a short, structured explanation (5\u20136 points) of why atomic radius decreases across period 3 (Na\u2192Cl) but ionisation enthalpy does not increase perfectly smoothly across the same period.\n\nQ56. For each of the following five statements, state True/False and give a one-line reason: (i) Electron gain enthalpy and electronegativity are the same physical quantity. (ii) The lowest-IE element in a group is always the strongest reducing agent in aqueous solution. (iii) A completely filled d-subshell always means the element is not a transition metal. (iv) Isoelectronic species always have identical chemical properties. (v) A larger $\\Delta\\chi$ always means a bond is more than 50% ionic.\n\n---\n\n# Part II \u2014 Consolidated Answer Key\n\n## Section 2.1 \u2014 Numerical-Answer Type\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|\n| 1 | 0285 | 9 | 260 | 17 | 50 |\n| 2 | 0625 | 10 | 46 | 18 | 60 |\n| 3 | 0760 | 11 | 4 | 19 | 3 |\n| 4 | +3 | 12 | 3.00 eV | 20 | 5 |\n| 5 | 7 | 13 | 69 | 21 | 4 |\n| 6 | 27 | 14 | -8 | 22 | 20 |\n| 7 | 217 | 15 | 2 |  |  |\n| 8 | 30 | 16 | 170 |  |  |\n\n## Section 2.2 \u2014 Single-Correct MCQs\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---:|---:|:---:|---:|:---:|\n| 1 | (a) | 6 | (b) | 11 | (b) |\n| 2 | (b) | 7 | (c) | 12 | (a) |\n| 3 | (b) | 8 | (d) | 13 | (b) |\n| 4 | (b) | 9 | (b) | 14 | (a) |\n| 5 | (b) | 10 | (b) | 15 | (a) |\n\n## Section 2.3 \u2014 Correct-Order Code Questions\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|:---|:---:|\n| CO-1 | 0020 |\n| CO-2 | 0015 |\n| CO-3 | 0053 |\n| CO-4 | 0027 |\n| CO-5 | 0049 |\n| CO-6 | 0037 |\n\n## Section 2.4 \u2014 Subjective / Long-Answer Problems\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|\n| 1 | 12 electrons | 15 | 7.45 | 29 | 3.50 eV | 43 | See solution |\n| 2 | 3.60 | 16 | 4.15 | 30 | See solution | 44 | MgCl\u2082; AgCl |\n| 3 | 230 kcal mol\u207b\u00b9 | 17 | 7.12 | 31 | See solution | 45 | -737.5 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 4 | -560 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 | 18 | See solution | 32 | 2.81 or 1.59* | 46 | 1.39 : 1 |\n| 5 | 7.20 | 19 | 2.145 \u00c5 | 33 | 2.76 | 47 | 0 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 6 | 4 | 20 | See solution | 34 | 2.84 | 48 | See solution |\n| 7 | 10 | 21 | See solution | 35 | 52.14%; 70.18% | 49 | CsCl |\n| 8 | 6.93 BM | 22 | Group 13; +3 | 36 | Basic | 50 | See solution |\n| 9 | 5.92 BM | 23 | See solution | 37 | 3.33; ethyne | 51 | 1150 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 10 | 2.83 BM | 24 | Valency 2 | 38 | 128.13 pm | 52 | Upper-right; see solution |\n| 11 | 13 | 25 | 122.4 eV | 39 | CF\u2083COOH | 53 | See solution |\n| 12 | 6.95 | 26 | Li: 160; Cs: 189 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 | 40 | Inert-pair effect | 54 | M\u2032 |\n| 13 | 7.85 | 27 | See solution | 41 | +2.5 | 55 | See solution |\n| 14 | 2.85 | 28 | See solution | 42 | Na\u2082O < Al\u2082O\u2083 < SO\u2083 | 56 | All false |\n\n\\*The Pauling bond-energy relation gives only $|\\Delta\\chi|$; the sign depends on which atom is assumed to be more electronegative.\n\n---\n\n# Part III \u2014 Worked Solutions\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.1\n\nS1. $\\sigma=(1\\times0.35)+(8\\times0.85)+(10\\times1.00)=17.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=20-17.15=\\mathbf{2.85}$ \u2192 0285\n\nS2. 3d electron of Fe ($3d^6$ group): $\\sigma=(5\\times0.35)+(18\\times1.00)=1.75+18=19.75\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=26-19.75=\\mathbf{6.25}$ \u2192 0625\n\nS3. 4p electron of Br ($[Ar]3d^{10}4s^24p^5$): same-group (4s,4p) others $=6\\times0.35=2.10$; $n{-}1$ shell (3s,3p,3d=18)$\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells (10)$\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=27.40\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=35-27.40=\\mathbf{7.60}$ \u2192 0760\n\nS4. Big jump between $IE_3$ and $IE_4$ \u2192 only 3 valence electrons removed easily \u2192 element is in Group 13-type pattern \u2192 stable oxidation state = +3\n\nS5. Positive $\\Delta_{eg}H$ up to Z=20: He, Be, N, Ne, Mg, Ar, Ca \u2192 7\n\nS6. Normal period-4 length = $4s(2)+3d(10)+4p(6)=18$. Scaling capacities by $3/2$: $4s=3,\\ 3d=15,\\ 4p=9$. Total $=3+15+9=\\mathbf{27}$\n\nS7. $Z_{eff}(\\text{P}, 3p)=15-(4\\times0.35+8\\times0.85+2\\times1.00)=15-10.20=4.80$. $\\chi_{AR}=\\dfrac{0.359\\times4.80}{1.10^2}+0.744=1.424+0.744=2.168\\approx2.17$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 217\n\nS8. $\\chi_M=(14.0+2.8)/2=8.4$ eV; $\\chi_P=8.4/2.8=\\mathbf{3.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 30\n\nS9. $\\Delta=72-\\sqrt{44\\times64}=72-53.06=18.94$; $|\\Delta\\chi|=0.208\\sqrt{18.94}=0.905$; $\\chi_B=3.50-0.905=\\mathbf{2.60}$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 260\n\nS10. $\\Delta\\chi=2.0$; $\\%=16(2.0)+3.5(2.0)^2=32+14=\\mathbf{46}$\n\nS11. $\\sqrt{n(n+2)}=4.90\\Rightarrow n(n+2)\\approx24\\Rightarrow n=4$ (check: $\\sqrt{4\\times6}=\\sqrt{24}=4.899\\approx4.90$) \u2192 4\n\nS12. Energy/atom $=9.6\\times10^{-13}/2\\times10^{6}=4.8\\times10^{-19}$ J; in eV $=4.8\\times10^{-19}/1.6\\times10^{-19}=\\mathbf{3.00\\ eV}$\n\nS13. $A^+\\to A^{5+}$ requires removing electrons via $IE_2+IE_3+IE_4+IE_5=9x+14x+20x+26x=\\mathbf{69x}$ \u2192 $a=$ 69\n\nS14. $-900=150+300+1200+3q-1350\\Rightarrow -900=300+3q\\Rightarrow q=-400$ kJ/mol; $q/50=\\mathbf{-8}$\n\nS15. $\\Delta H_{sol}=780-430-295=55$ kcal/mol $=0.55\\times10^x\\Rightarrow10^x=100\\Rightarrow x=\\mathbf{2}$\n\nS16. K, 4s electron: $\\sigma=(0)(0.35)+(8)(0.85)+(10)(1.00)=16.80\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=19-16.80=2.20$. N, 2p electron: $\\sigma=(4)(0.35)+(2)(0.85)=1.40+1.70=3.10\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=7-3.10=3.90$. Difference $=|3.90-2.20|=1.70$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 170\n\nS17. Ratio of %s-character $=50/25=2\\Rightarrow\\chi_{sp}=2\\times2.50=\\mathbf{5.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 50\n\nS18. $80/200=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})=15\\times0.4=\\mathbf{6.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 60\n\nS19. $\\text{Cr}^{3+}(d^3,3\\uparrow)$\u2713, $\\text{Mn}^{2+}(d^5,5\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}(d^5,5\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{Co}^{2+}(d^7,3\\uparrow)$\u2713, $\\text{Ni}^{2+}(d^8,2\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{V}^{2+}(d^3,3\\uparrow)$\u2713 \u2192 3\n\nS20. $\\text{Zn}^{2+}(d^{10})$\u2713, $\\text{Sc}^{3+}(d^0)$\u2713, $\\text{Ti}^{4+}(d^0)$\u2713, $\\text{Cu}^+(d^{10})$\u2713, $\\text{Fe}^{2+}(d^6,\\text{4 unpaired})$\u2717, $\\text{Mn}^{7+}(d^0)$\u2713 \u2192 5\n\nS21. 31=Ga(p)\u2713, 47=Ag(d)\u2717, 56=Ba(s)\u2717, 82=Pb(p)\u2713, 36=Kr(p)\u2713, 92=U(f)\u2717, 15=P(p)\u2713 \u2192 4\n\nS22. Ag = $[Kr]4d^{10}5s^1$ = full config $1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^{10}4s^24p^64d^{10}5s^1$. d-electrons $=3d^{10}+4d^{10}=\\mathbf{20}$\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.2\n\nS1. **Answer: (a).** Across Period 2, first ionisation enthalpy generally increases. Boron is lower than beryllium because the electron removed from B is a higher-energy $2p$ electron, whereas Be has a stable filled $2s^2$ subshell. Therefore, $\\text{B}<\\text{Be}<\\text{C}<\\text{N}$.\n\nS2. **Answer: (b).** Gallium is slightly smaller than aluminium because the intervening $3d$ electrons shield poorly, increasing $Z_{eff}$ on Ga. Down the rest of the group, additional shells increase size. Hence $\\text{Ga}<\\text{Al}<\\text{In}<\\text{Tl}$.\n\nS3. **Answer: (b).** Zinc has $3d^{10}4s^2$, and its common ion $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ is $3d^{10}$. Neither has an incomplete d-subshell, so Zn is not a transition element under the strict definition.\n\nS4. **Answer: (b).** Hf follows the lanthanoids. Poor shielding by the filled $4f$ subshell causes lanthanoid contraction, making the radii of Zr and Hf nearly identical.\n\nS5. **Answer: (b).** Chlorine has the greatest electron-gain-enthalpy magnitude because its roomier $3p$ subshell experiences less electron-electron repulsion than F's compact $2p$ subshell. The order is $\\text{Cl}>\\text{F}>\\text{Br}>\\text{I}$.\n\nS6. **Answer: (b).** Electronegativity increases with s-character because an s-orbital holds electron density closer to the nucleus. Since s-character follows $sp(50\\%)>sp^2(33.3\\%)>sp^3(25\\%)$, the electronegativity order is $sp>sp^2>sp^3$.\n\nS7. **Answer: (c).** $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}$ is basic, $\\text{SO}_3$ and $\\text{Cl}_2\\text{O}_7$ are acidic, while $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$ reacts with both acids and bases and is therefore amphoteric.\n\nS8. **Answer: (d).** All four species contain 10 electrons. In an isoelectronic series, radius decreases as nuclear charge increases. Mg has the highest nuclear charge, so $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ is the smallest.\n\nS9. **Answer: (b).** The inert-pair effect stabilises lower oxidation states down a p-block group. Thus Tl(I) is more stable than Tl(III).\n\nS10. **Answer: (b).** Down Group 17, the H-X bond becomes longer and weaker, so proton release becomes easier. Therefore, aqueous acid strength follows $\\text{HI}>\\text{HBr}>\\text{HCl}>\\text{HF}$.\n\nS11. **Answer: (b).** Adding an electron to $\\text{O}^-$ requires overcoming repulsion from an already negatively charged ion. Consequently, the second electron gain enthalpy is always positive.\n\nS12. **Answer: (a).** Be\u00b2\u207a is smaller and has greater polarising power than Mg\u00b2\u207a. It distorts the electron cloud of Cl\u207b more strongly, making $\\text{BeCl}_2$ more covalent.\n\nS13. **Answer: (b).** Antimony lies along the conventional metal-non-metal boundary and is classified as a metalloid.\n\nS14. **Answer: (a).** A very large jump immediately after $IE_1$ means one valence electron is removed easily and the second would come from a stable inner shell. The element therefore belongs to Group 1.\n\nS15. **Answer: (a).** For ions with equal charges and the same anion, lattice-enthalpy magnitude decreases as cation size increases. Thus $\\text{LiCl}>\\text{NaCl}>\\text{KCl}>\\text{RbCl}$.\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.3\n\nCO-1: Row 1 \u2713 (Al\u00b3\u207a smallest, isoelectronic-like cation series), Row 2 \u2713 (down-group increase), Row 3 \u2717 (N\u00b3\u207b has lowest Z among this isoelectronic trio, so it should be largest, not smallest \u2014 order is reversed), Row 4 \u2713 (higher charge \u2192 smaller radius), Row 5 \u2717 (hydration magnitude actually falls down the group: Li\u207a>Na\u207a>K\u207a>Rb\u207a, so ascending order is wrong). Correct rows: 1,2,4 \u2192 Sum = 05+12+03 = 0020\n\nCO-2: Rows 1\u20135 are all correct standard results (Be>B and N>O are the classic IE special cases; Cl>F and S>Se follow the normal EGE-magnitude trend from period 2\u21923 onward; F>Cl is the standard EN trend). Row 6 is wrong \u2014 S's EGE magnitude (200) is greater than O's (141), so \"S<O\" is false. Only incorrect row: 6 \u2192 Sum = 0015\n\nCO-3: Row 1 \u2713 (lanthanide-contraction twin). Row 2 \u2713 (no f-electrons yet at La, so no contraction interrupts the normal group increase). Row 3 \u2717 (Zn (137 pm) is actually larger than Cu (128 pm) \u2014 the completed $3d^{10}4s^2$ pushes size back up). Row 4 \u2713 (Eu is anomalously large due to stable half-filled $4f^7$). Row 5 \u2713 (higher charge, smaller radius). Row 6 \u2713 (La is the largest lanthanoid, Lu the smallest \u2014 steady contraction). Correct rows: 1,2,4,5,6 \u2192 Sum = 07+13+05+18+10 = 0053\n\nCO-4: Row 1 \u2713 correct period-3 acidity progression. Row 2 \u2713 higher oxidation state, more acidic. Row 3 \u2713 bond-strength-controlled hydracid trend. Row 4 \u2717 \u2014 NH\u2083 is actually more basic than PH\u2083 (N's lone pair is more concentrated/available despite N being more electronegative); the stated order is reversed. Row 5 \u2713 higher oxidation state of S, more acidic. Row 6 \u2717 \u2014 Bi(III) is more stable than Bi(V) due to the inert-pair effect; Bi(V) is a strong oxidiser, so the stated order is reversed. Incorrect rows: 4,6 \u2192 Sum = 08+19 = 0027\n\nCO-5: Row 1 \u2713 %s-character rule. Row 2 \u2713 higher bond order, higher effective EN. Row 3 \u2717 \u2014 F is more electronegative than N, so in NF\u2083 the bond polarises toward F, away from N (opposite of NH\u2083); the statement is false. Row 4 \u2713 EN rises with positive charge. Row 5 \u2713 classic Ga>Al special case. Row 6 \u2713 classic Hg>Cd>Zn special case. Correct rows: 1,2,4,5,6 \u2192 Sum = 03+14+06+09+17 = 0049\n\nCO-6: Row 1 \u2713 \u2014 for a fixed anion, lattice-enthalpy magnitude decreases as cation size increases. Row 2 \u2713 \u2014 MgO has a much larger charge product than NaCl. Row 3 \u2713 \u2014 hydration-enthalpy magnitude decreases down Group 1. Row 4 \u2717 \u2014 ionic mobility in water increases down Group 1 because the strongly hydrated Li\u207a ion has the largest effective hydrated radius. Row 5 \u2717 \u2014 NaCl has a greater lattice-enthalpy magnitude than CsCl because Na\u207a is smaller. Row 6 \u2717 \u2014 CaO has a greater lattice-enthalpy magnitude than BaO because Ca\u00b2\u207a is smaller. Incorrect rows: 4, 5 and 6 \u2192 Sum = 16+08+13 = 0037.\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.4: Q1-Q6\n\nS1. $\\text{Fe}^{3+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5=1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^5$. p-electrons $=2p^6+3p^6=\\mathbf{12}$\n\nS2. $Z_{eff}(\\text{N},2p)=7-3.10=3.90$ (from calc in 2.1-S16). $\\chi_{AR}=\\dfrac{0.359\\times3.90}{0.70^2}+0.744=\\dfrac{1.400}{0.49}+0.744=2.857+0.744=\\mathbf{3.60}$\n\nS3. $\\Delta H_{sol}=\\text{Lattice}_{diss}+\\Delta H_{hyd}(A^+)+\\Delta H_{hyd}(B^-)$ $15=\\text{Lattice}_{diss}+(-120)+(-95)\\Rightarrow \\text{Lattice}_{diss}=15+215=\\mathbf{230\\ kcal/mol}$\n\nS4. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+BDE+IE_{sum}+2\\times EA+\\Delta H_{latt}$ $-650=180+190+1400+2EA+(-1300)$ $-650=470+2EA\\Rightarrow EA=\\mathbf{-560\\ kJ/mol\\ per\\ X\\ atom}$\n\nS5. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+BDE+IE_1+EA+U$ $-380=90+120+480+(-350)+U\\Rightarrow-380=340+U\\Rightarrow U=\\mathbf{-720\\ kJ/mol}$ $-U/100=\\mathbf{7.20}$\n\nS6. Checking each: (i) T \u2014 H\u2013F is the strongest H\u2013X bond. (ii) T \u2014 bond angles: NH\u2083(107\u00b0)>PH\u2083(93.5\u00b0)>AsH\u2083(91.8\u00b0). (iii) T \u2014 mobility rises down the group (Section 1.9). (iv) F \u2014 real order is $\\text{Cl}_2>\\text{Br}_2>\\text{F}_2>\\text{I}_2$, not monotonic; F\u2082's bond is anomalously weak (lone-pair repulsion). (v) F \u2014 Sc\u00b3\u207a(~74.5 pm) is larger than Ti\u2074\u207a(~60.5 pm); statement reversed. (vi) T \u2014 higher oxidation state of N, more acidic. (vii) F \u2014 hydration magnitude actually falls down the group (Be\u00b2\u207a highest); statement reversed. (viii) F \u2014 Cu\u00b2\u207a is more stable than Cu\u207a in water (Cu\u207a disproportionates); statement reversed. (ix) F \u2014 I\u207b is the strongest reducing halide ion, F\u207b the weakest; statement reversed. (x) F \u2014 by Fajans' rule BeCl\u2082 (smallest cation) is most covalent, not least; statement reversed.\n\n$x(\\text{correct})=4$ [(i),(ii),(iii),(vi)], $y(\\text{incorrect})=6$ [(iv),(v),(vii),(viii),(ix),(x)]. $|x-y|^2=|4-6|^2=\\mathbf{4}$\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.4: Q7-Q56\n\nS7. $\\text{Cu}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^{10}4s^1$. Electrons with $\\ell=2$ (d-electrons) $=3d^{10}=\\mathbf{10}$.\n\nS8. $\\text{Cr}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^54s^1$ \u2014 all 5 d-electrons unpaired (Hund's rule, degenerate orbitals) plus the single 4s electron is also unpaired. Total unpaired $=\\mathbf{6}$. $\\mu_{so}=\\sqrt{6\\times8}=\\sqrt{48}=\\mathbf{6.93\\ BM}$.\n\nS9. $\\text{Mn}^{2+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5$ \u2192 5 unpaired electrons. $\\mu=\\sqrt{5\\times7}=\\sqrt{35}=\\mathbf{5.92\\ BM}$.\n\nS10. $\\text{Ni}^{2+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^8$ \u2192 fill 5 orbitals with 8 electrons: 3 pairs + 2 singles \u2192 2 unpaired. $\\mu=\\sqrt{2\\times4}=\\sqrt8=\\mathbf{2.83\\ BM}$.\n\nS11. $\\text{Fe}^{3+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5=1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^5$. Electrons with $n=3$: $3s^2+3p^6+3d^5=2+6+5=\\mathbf{13}$.\n\nS12. Se $=(1s^2)(2s^22p^6)(3s^23p^6)(3d^{10})(4s^24p^4)$. 4p electron: same group (4s+4p\u22121)$=5\\times0.35=1.75$; $(n{-}1)$ shell $(3s3p3d=18)\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells $(10)\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=27.05\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=34-27.05=\\mathbf{6.95}$.\n\nS13. Cu, 3d electron ($3d^{10}4s^1$, use $nd$ rule): same-group others $=9\\times0.35=3.15$; groups to the left (18 electrons) $\\times1.00=18.00$; the 4s electron (to the right) shields zero. $\\sigma=21.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=29-21.15=\\mathbf{7.85}$.\n\nS14. Mg, 3s: same group others $=1\\times0.35=0.35$; $(n{-}1)$ shell (8) $\\times0.85=6.80$; lower (2)$\\times1.00=2.00$. $\\sigma=9.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=12-9.15=\\mathbf{2.85}$.\n\nS15. Ar, 3p: same group others $=5\\times0.35=1.75$; $(n{-}1)$ shell (8)$\\times0.85=6.80$; lower (2)$\\times1.00=2.00$. $\\sigma=10.55\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=18-10.55=\\mathbf{7.45}$.\n\nS16. $Z_{eff}(3d)=7.85$ (from S13). For the 4s electron: same-group others $=0$ (only one 4s electron, no 4p) $\\times0.35=0$; $(n{-}1)$ shell now includes the full $3d^{10}$ ($3s^23p^63d^{10}=18$) $\\times0.85=15.30$; lower (10)$\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=25.30\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(4s)=29-25.30=3.70$. Difference $=7.85-3.70=\\mathbf{4.15}$. This large gap is exactly why the 4s electron is lost first when Cu forms Cu\u207a/Cu\u00b2\u207a, even though 4s filled before 3d.\n\nS17. $68/172=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/18\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})=18\\times(68/172)=\\mathbf{7.12}$.\n\nS18. Zr $=[\\text{Kr}]4d^25s^2$; Hf $=[\\text{Xe}]4f^{14}5d^26s^2$. Going from period 5 to period 6 across this pair, 14 additional 4f electrons had to be filled in between (the lanthanoids), and 4f electrons shield very poorly. The resulting steady rise in $Z_{eff}$ (lanthanide contraction) very nearly cancels the size increase expected simply from adding a whole new principal shell \u2014 leaving Zr and Hf almost identical in size and chemistry (a \"chemical twin\" pair).\n\nS19. $d_{A-B}=r_A+r_B-0.09\\Delta\\chi = 1.20+0.99-0.09(0.5)=2.19-0.045=\\mathbf{2.145\\ \\text{\u00c5}}$ (shorter than the simple sum $r_A+r_B=2.19$ \u00c5, because bond polarity contracts the bond).\n\nS20. $\\text{Fe}\\to\\text{Fe}^{2+}$: same nucleus (26 protons), but 2 fewer electrons, so remaining electrons feel higher $Z_{eff}$ per electron and less mutual repulsion \u2192 smaller radius. $\\text{Fe}^{2+}\\to\\text{Fe}^{3+}$: one further electron removed, $Z_{eff}$ per remaining electron rises again \u2192 radius shrinks further. Hence $r(\\text{Fe})>r(\\text{Fe}^{2+})>r(\\text{Fe}^{3+})$, consistent with the general rule $M>M^{2+}>M^{3+}$.\n\nS21. Higher bond order packs more bonding electron density between the two nuclei, pulling them closer together and shortening the bond ($r\\propto1/\\text{bond order}$); it also raises the %s-character of the hybrid orbitals involved (roughly $sp^3\\to sp^2\\to sp$ across single\u2192double\u2192triple N\u2013N bonds), and s-orbitals hold density closer to the nucleus, reinforcing the same contraction. Hence single > double > triple in bond length.\n\nS22. Jump between $IE_3(25.0)$ and $IE_4(45.0)$ is the largest relative jump (1.8\u00d7), meaning 3 valence electrons are removed comparatively easily before hitting the core. Likely group 13, stable oxidation state +3.\n\nS23. Be's electron is removed from a filled, symmetric, comparatively low-energy $2s^2$ subshell, while B's removed electron is a $2p^1$ electron \u2014 higher in energy and less penetrating than a 2s electron (even though B has one more proton). The penetration/subshell effect outweighs the extra nuclear charge here.\n\nS24. Giant jump appears between $IE_2(1450)$ and $IE_3(7732)$ \u2014 a jump of over 5\u00d7. This means 2 valence electrons are removed easily, and the 3rd comes from a stable inner (noble-gas) core. Valency = 2 (this data matches Mg).\n\nS25. $IE=13.6\\times Z^2/n^2 = 13.6\\times9/1=\\mathbf{122.4\\ eV}$.\n\nS26. Li: $159+520-519=\\mathbf{160}$ kJ/mol (net). Cs: $76+376-263=\\mathbf{189}$ kJ/mol (net). Even though Cs has the lower gas-phase $IE_1$, once atomisation and hydration are folded in, Li's overall cycle (160 kJ/mol) is more favourable (lower net cost) than Cs's (189 kJ/mol) \u2014 Li\u207a's very large hydration enthalpy is the deciding term, making Li the stronger reducing agent in aqueous solution despite its higher gas-phase IE.\n\nS27. The extra 46 kJ/mol advantage for Cl ($-349$ vs $-328$) arises because the incoming electron in Cl enters the roomier, less-crowded $3p$ orbital, whereas in F it must squeeze into the very compact $2p$ orbital, where electron\u2013electron repulsion partially cancels the benefit of F's smaller size/higher $Z_{eff}$.\n\nS28. The positive $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{O})$ (endothermic, since an electron is being pushed onto an already-negative $\\text{O}^-$ ion) is a small energy cost compared to the very large exothermic lattice enthalpy released when $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ and $\\text{O}^{2-}$ ions assemble into the MgO crystal ($-3795$ kJ/mol). Once you sum the full Born\u2013Haber cycle, the large negative lattice term more than compensates for the unfavourable second electron-gain step, giving an overall favourable (exothermic) formation of solid MgO.\n\nS29. Energy/atom $=1.68\\times10^{-12}/3\\times10^6=5.6\\times10^{-19}$ J. In eV: $5.6\\times10^{-19}/1.6\\times10^{-19}=\\mathbf{3.50\\ eV}$.\n\nS30. N has a stable, symmetric half-filled $2p^3$ configuration; adding an electron forces pairing in an already-settled arrangement, which costs more than it gains \u2014 making $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{N})$ positive (unfavourable). P has the same $np^3$ symmetry, but its larger, roomier $3p$ orbital accommodates the extra electron with far less crowding/repulsion than N's compact $2p$, so despite the same \"half-filled resists addition\" effect, P's value still comes out favourable (negative).\n\nS31. Both He ($1s^2$) and Ne ($2s^22p^6$) must start an entirely new, higher-energy shell to accept an electron \u2014 both processes are unfavourable. But Ne's incoming electron would enter the $n=3$ shell, which is shielded by two full inner shells (10 electrons) and sits considerably farther from a nucleus of only $Z=10$; He's incoming electron enters $n=2$, shielded by just 2 inner electrons around a nucleus of $Z=2$. The proportionally weaker net attraction available to Ne's new-shell electron (in a poorer $Z_{eff}$-to-distance ratio) makes Ne's electron gain even less favourable than He's.\n\nS32. $\\Delta=145-\\sqrt{150\\times80}=145-109.54=35.46$; $|\\Delta\\chi|=0.102\\sqrt{35.46}=0.607$. Since $\\Delta$ came out positive and small, $\\chi_A\\approx\\chi_B\\pm0.61$; taking A as the more electronegative partner (consistent with $\\chi_B=2.20$ given), $\\chi_A\\approx2.20+0.61=\\mathbf{2.81}$ (or $2.20-0.61=1.59$, depending on which atom is assumed more electronegative \u2014 state your assumption clearly, as the Pauling relation only gives $|\\Delta\\chi|$, not the sign).\n\nS33. $\\chi_M=(1140+349)/(2\\times96.5)=1489/193=\\mathbf{7.72}$ (this is on the same numerical footing as an eV-based value even though computed from kJ/mol, because of how the conversion factor is built in). Converting: $\\chi_P\\approx7.72/2.8=\\mathbf{2.76}$ \u2014 reasonably close to Cl's accepted Pauling value of 3.16, illustrating that the Mulliken\u2192Pauling conversion is approximate.\n\nS34. $\\chi_{AR}=0.359\\times7.60/(1.14)^2+0.744 = 2.7284/1.2996+0.744=2.100+0.744=\\mathbf{2.84}$.\n\nS35. $\\Delta\\chi=3.7-1.5=2.2$. (a) Hannay\u2013Smith: $16(2.2)+3.5(2.2)^2=35.2+16.94=\\mathbf{52.14\\%}$. (b) Pauling exponential: $[1-e^{-0.25(2.2)^2}]\\times100=[1-e^{-1.21}]\\times100=[1-0.2982]\\times100=\\mathbf{70.18\\%}$. The two models diverge noticeably at large $\\Delta\\chi$ \u2014 a reminder that %-ionic-character estimates are approximate models, not exact measurements, and different formulas can give quite different numbers for the same $\\Delta\\chi$.\n\nS36. $|\\chi_O-\\chi_K|=|3.44-0.82|=2.62$; $|\\chi_O-\\chi_H|=|3.44-2.20|=1.24$. Since $|\\chi_O-\\chi_K|>|\\chi_O-\\chi_H|$, the K\u2013O bond is the more polar (weaker/more ionic) link and breaks first, releasing $\\text{K}^++\\text{OH}^-$ \u2014 KOH is basic, exactly analogous to NaOH/CsOH.\n\nS37. Ratio of %s-character $=33.3/25=1.332\\Rightarrow\\chi_{sp^2}=1.332\\times2.50=\\mathbf{3.33}$ (under the stated simplified proportionality). The most acidic C\u2013H bond is in ethyne ($sp$ carbon, 50% s-character) \u2014 its conjugate base (acetylide, $\\text{HC}{\\equiv}\\text{C}^-$) holds the negative charge in an orbital closest to the carbon nucleus among the three, which stabilises the anion most and makes proton loss easiest.\n\nS38. $d_{C-F}=77+64-9(3.98-2.55)=141-9(1.43)=141-12.87=\\mathbf{128.13\\ pm}$ (noticeably shorter than the naive sum of 141 pm, because of the large C\u2013F electronegativity difference).\n\nS39. $\\text{CF}_3\\text{COOH}$ is the stronger acid. The $-\\text{CF}_3$ group is strongly electron-withdrawing (high group electronegativity, \u22483.46, vs \u22482.30 for $-\\text{CH}_3$), which pulls electron density away from the carboxylate oxygen, stabilising the conjugate base ($\\text{CF}_3\\text{COO}^-$) far more effectively than $-\\text{CH}_3$ stabilises $\\text{CH}_3\\text{COO}^-$ \u2014 a more stable conjugate base means a stronger acid.\n\nS40. The effect is the inert-pair effect. Down groups 13 and 14, the outer $ns^2$ pair becomes progressively less willing to participate in bonding (poor shielding by intervening d/f electrons plus relativistic stabilisation), so the lower oxidation state (Tl(I), Pb(II)) becomes the thermodynamically preferred one. Consequently the higher states (Tl(III), Pb(IV)) are relatively unstable and tend to be reduced back to the inert-pair-favoured lower state \u2014 which is exactly what makes them oxidising agents.\n\nS41. Let average S oxidation state be $x$: charge balance gives $4x+6(-2)=-2\\Rightarrow4x=10\\Rightarrow x=+2.5$. This is only an average \u2014 tetrathionate actually contains two distinct types of sulfur: two central S atoms behave like $0$-ish (S\u2013S bonded, similar to elemental sulfur) and two terminal $-\\text{SO}_3^-$-type sulfurs behave close to $+5$, averaging to $+2.5$ overall, just as $\\text{Fe}_3\\text{O}_4$'s average $+8/3$ hides a real mixture of Fe(II) and Fe(III).\n\nS42. $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}<\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{SO}_3$ in acidic character. Na (very low EN, strongly electropositive) forms a highly ionic, strongly basic oxide. Al sits near the metal/non-metal boundary; its oxide is amphoteric \u2014 sitting between basic and acidic. S, a non-metal in its highest (+6) oxidation state, forms a fully covalent, strongly acidic oxide (reacts with water to give $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4$). This tracks the steady rise in central-atom electronegativity/oxidation state across the period.\n\nS43. (a) HI vs HF acidity in water is bond-strength controlled: I is much larger than F, so the H\u2013I bond is far longer/weaker than H\u2013F, making H\u207a easier to release from HI \u2014 this happens despite F being far more electronegative than I. (b) HF vs $\\text{CH}_4$ (C\u2013H) is electronegativity controlled: within the same period/similar bond lengths, F's much higher electronegativity polarises the H\u2013F bond far more strongly, favouring proton release, while C\u2013H is barely polarised at all. The key point: the same-looking comparison (\"which acid is stronger\") is governed by an entirely different physical factor depending on whether you're comparing down a group or across a period.\n\nS44. (a) $\\text{MgCl}_2$ has greater covalent character than $\\text{CaCl}_2$ \u2014 $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ is smaller than $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ (same charge), so it polarises the $\\text{Cl}^-$ electron cloud more strongly. (b) $\\text{AgCl}$ has greater covalent character than $\\text{NaCl}$ even at similar cation radius \u2014 $\\text{Ag}^+$ has a filled but poorly-shielding $4d^{10}$ (\"pseudo-noble-gas\") core, unlike $\\text{Na}^+$'s genuinely noble-gas $[\\text{Ne}]$ core, so $\\text{Ag}^+$ polarises $\\text{Cl}^-$ more strongly for a given size.\n\nS45. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_1+\\tfrac12D(\\text{Br}_2)+\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Br})+U_{latt(form)}$ $-361.4=108.4+495.8+96.4+(-324.5)+U$ $-361.4=376.1+U\\Rightarrow U=\\mathbf{-737.5\\ kJ/mol}$\n\nS46. Ratio $=\\dfrac{z^2/r(\\text{Mg}^{2+})}{z^2/r(\\text{Ca}^{2+})}=\\dfrac{4/72}{4/100}=\\dfrac{100}{72}=\\mathbf{1.39:1}$ \u2014 i.e. $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$'s hydration enthalpy magnitude is about 1.39\u00d7 that of $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$, consistent with Mg\u00b2\u207a's smaller size and higher charge density.\n\nS47. $\\Delta H_{sol}=690+(-380)+(-310)=690-690=\\mathbf{0\\ kJ/mol}$. A near-zero $\\Delta H_{sol}$ means lattice-breaking and hydration are almost perfectly balanced enthalpically \u2014 in this borderline case, solubility is decided almost entirely by the entropy term ($\\Delta G=\\Delta H-T\\Delta S$), not by enthalpy at all, since $\\Delta H_{sol}\\approx0$ gives essentially no enthalpic driving force either way.\n\nS48. $\\text{LiF}>\\text{NaF}>\\text{KF}>\\text{RbF}$ (fixed anion, cation size rising down the group \u2192 lattice enthalpy magnitude falls) is controlled by cation size. $\\text{NaF}>\\text{NaCl}>\\text{NaBr}>\\text{NaI}$ (fixed cation, anion size rising down the group) is controlled by anion size. Both orders follow the same underlying rule ($|U|\\propto1/(r_++r_-)$), but each isolates a different ion as the size-changing variable.\n\nS49. By Fajans' rules, $\\text{Li}^+$ (smallest, most highly-charge-dense alkali cation) polarises $\\text{Cl}^-$ the most strongly, giving LiCl the most covalent character among the alkali chlorides; $\\text{Cs}^+$ is large and weakly polarising, so CsCl stays closest to purely ionic bonding. Greater covalent character generally lowers melting point (more molecular-like, less extended lattice character), so despite naive charge/size reasoning suggesting the small $\\text{Li}^+$ should give the strongest lattice, the covalency effect dominates and CsCl has the higher melting point of the two (consistent with real values: LiCl \u2248 605\u00b0C, CsCl \u2248 645\u00b0C).\n\nS50. $\\text{Li}^+$'s small size gives it a very high charge density, so it attracts and binds a thick, tightly-held shell of water molecules \u2014 its effective (hydrated) radius moving through solution ends up larger than $\\text{Cs}^+$'s. $\\text{Cs}^+$, despite being physically bigger as a bare ion, is weakly hydrated and drags a much thinner water shell, giving it a smaller effective size and therefore higher mobility. Bare-ion size and effective (hydrodynamic) size are simply two different quantities.\n\nS51. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_1+IE_2+D(\\text{Cl}_2)+2\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Cl})+U_{latt(form)}$ $-796=178+590+IE_2+242+2(-349)+(-2258)$ $-796=178+590+IE_2+242-698-2258$ $-796=-1946+IE_2\\Rightarrow IE_2=\\mathbf{1150\\ kJ/mol}$\n\nS52. High $IE_1$, high EN, small radius, and an acidic covalent oxide are all hallmarks of a non-metal from the upper-right region of the periodic table (near the halogens/chalcogens). Its hydride would be expected to be: (i) a covalent, molecular compound (not an ionic salt-like hydride), and (ii) acidic in water (or at least the central atom polarises the H\u2013E bond strongly), following the same logic as $\\text{HF}, \\text{H}_2\\text{O}$ etc.\n\nS53. Since P has lower $IE_1$ and lower EN than Q in the same period, P sits to the left of Q. (a) P has the larger atomic radius (radius falls left\u2192right across a period). (b) P forms the more basic oxide (lower EN/more metallic character \u2192 more ionic, basic oxide). (c) P is more likely to act as a reducing agent (lower IE \u2192 loses electrons more readily).\n\nS54. M\u2032 has the smaller cation. A smaller, more highly-charge-dense cation polarises the shared $\\text{Cl}^-$ electron cloud more strongly (Fajans' rules), pulling the bonding toward covalent character \u2014 which lowers water solubility and increases covalency, exactly matching M\u2032's described behaviour. (This is the same logic as $\\text{BeCl}_2$ vs $\\text{CaCl}_2$, or $\\text{MgCl}_2$ vs $\\text{BaCl}_2$.)\n\nS55. (i) $Z_{eff}$ rises fairly smoothly across the period because each added electron enters the same $n=3$ shell and same-shell shielding is weak \u2014 so radius falls in a fairly regular, monotonic way. (ii) Ionisation enthalpy depends on $Z_{eff}$ and on which specific subshell/orbital is being emptied. (iii) Going from Mg to Al, the electron removed switches from a penetrating, stable filled $3s^2$ to a less-penetrating, exposed $3p^1$ \u2014 a local dip, even though $Z_{eff}$ rose. (iv) Going from P to S, the electron removed switches from a stable, symmetric half-filled $3p^3$ to a paired $3p^4$, where extra electron\u2013electron repulsion makes removal easier \u2014 another local dip. (v) So radius (which only cares about the \"envelope\" of $Z_{eff}$ vs shell) decreases smoothly, while IE (which cares about the specific subshell/pairing state of the outgoing electron) shows the two well-known zig-zags at Mg\u2192Al and P\u2192S superimposed on the overall rising trend.\n\nS56. (i) False \u2014 EN describes a bonded atom (relative, dimensionless); electron gain enthalpy is a measurable energy change for an isolated gaseous atom. (ii) False \u2014 the classic counter-example is Li vs Cs: Li has the highest gas-phase $IE_1$ in its group, yet is the strongest reducing agent in water because of its very large hydration enthalpy. (iii) False \u2014 Zn, Cd, Hg have completely filled $d^{10}$ subshells in both atom and common ion, and are indeed excluded from the strict transition-metal definition, but this is a specific named special case, not a universal rule for every filled-d-subshell case (e.g. Cu\u207a has $d^{10}$ too but Cu is still classified as a transition element because the element Cu, i.e. Cu\u00b2\u207a/Cu\u2070, has incomplete d-subshells in its other common states). (iv) False \u2014 isoelectronic species (same electron count) can have very different chemical behaviour (e.g. $\\text{Na}^+$ is chemically inert-ish in solution while $\\text{F}^-$ is a base); they share electron count, not chemistry. (v) False \u2014 a larger $\\Delta\\chi$ generally correlates with more ionic character, but there's no universal sharp cutoff at which a bond flips to \"more than 50% ionic\"; different empirical formulas (Hannay\u2013Smith vs Pauling's exponential) can give quite different %-ionic-character estimates for the same $\\Delta\\chi$, as seen in Q35.\n";
const RELEASE = "periodicity-question-bank-v1";

type HeadingBlock = { kind: "heading"; level: number; text: string; id?: string };
type ParagraphBlock = { kind: "paragraph"; text: string };
type RuleBlock = { kind: "rule" };
type TableBlock = { kind: "table"; header: string[]; rows: string[][] };
type Block = HeadingBlock | ParagraphBlock | RuleBlock | TableBlock;

function slugify(value: string): string {
  return value
    .toLowerCase()
    .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, "-")
    .replace(/^-+|-+$/g, "");
}

function parseMarkdown(source: string): Block[] {
  const lines = source.replace(/\r\n/g, "\n").split("\n");
  const blocks: Block[] = [];
  let index = 0;

  while (index < lines.length) {
    const line = lines[index].trimEnd();

    if (!line.trim()) {
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    if (/^---+$/.test(line.trim())) {
      blocks.push({ kind: "rule" });
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    const heading = /^(#{1,4})\s+(.+)$/.exec(line);
    if (heading) {
      const text = heading[2].trim();
      blocks.push({
        kind: "heading",
        level: heading[1].length,
        text,
        id: text.startsWith("Part ") ? slugify(text) : undefined,
      });
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    if (line.trimStart().startsWith("|") && index + 1 < lines.length) {
      const divider = lines[index + 1].trim();
      if (/^\|?\s*:?-{3,}/.test(divider)) {
        const tableLines: string[] = [line];
        index += 2;
        while (index < lines.length && lines[index].trimStart().startsWith("|")) {
          tableLines.push(lines[index].trimEnd());
          index += 1;
        }
        const cells = (row: string) =>
          row
            .trim()
            .replace(/^\|/, "")
            .replace(/\|$/, "")
            .split("|")
            .map((cell) => cell.trim());
        blocks.push({
          kind: "table",
          header: cells(tableLines[0]),
          rows: tableLines.slice(1).map(cells),
        });
        continue;
      }
    }

    const paragraph: string[] = [line.trim()];
    index += 1;
    while (index < lines.length) {
      const next = lines[index].trimEnd();
      if (!next.trim()) break;
      if (/^(#{1,4})\s+/.test(next) || /^---+$/.test(next.trim())) break;
      if (next.trimStart().startsWith("|") && index + 1 < lines.length && /^\|?\s*:?-{3,}/.test(lines[index + 1].trim())) break;
      paragraph.push(next.trim());
      index += 1;
    }
    blocks.push({ kind: "paragraph", text: paragraph.join(" ") });
  }

  return blocks;
}

function renderMath(source: string): string {
  try {
    return katex.renderToString(source, {
      throwOnError: false,
      strict: "ignore",
      output: "html",
    });
  } catch {
    return source;
  }
}

function renderPlainSegment(text: string, keyPrefix: string): React.ReactNode[] {
  const chunks = text.split(/(\*\*[^*]+\*\*|`[^`]+`)/g).filter(Boolean);
  return chunks.map((chunk, index) => {
    const key = `${keyPrefix}-plain-${index}`;
    if (chunk.startsWith("**") && chunk.endsWith("**")) {
      return <strong key={key}>{chunk.slice(2, -2)}</strong>;
    }
    if (chunk.startsWith("`") && chunk.endsWith("`")) {
      return <code key={key}>{chunk.slice(1, -1)}</code>;
    }
    return <React.Fragment key={key}>{chunk}</React.Fragment>;
  });
}

function InlineContent({ text }: { text: string }) {
  const chunks = text.split(/(\$[^$\n]+\$)/g).filter(Boolean);
  return (
    <>
      {chunks.map((chunk, index) => {
        const key = `inline-${index}`;
        if (chunk.startsWith("$") && chunk.endsWith("$")) {
          return (
            <span
              key={key}
              className="qbankMath"
              dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: renderMath(chunk.slice(1, -1)) }}
            />
          );
        }
        return <React.Fragment key={key}>{renderPlainSegment(chunk, key)}</React.Fragment>;
      })}
    </>
  );
}

function QuestionBankTable({ block }: { block: TableBlock }) {
  return (
    <div className="qbankTableWrap">
      <table className="qbankTable">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            {block.header.map((cell, index) => (
              <th key={`head-${index}`}><InlineContent text={cell} /></th>
            ))}
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {block.rows.map((row, rowIndex) => (
            <tr key={`row-${rowIndex}`}>
              {row.map((cell, cellIndex) => (
                <td key={`cell-${rowIndex}-${cellIndex}`}><InlineContent text={cell} /></td>
              ))}
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  );
}

function JumpButton({ target, children }: { target: string; children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      onClick={() => document.getElementById(target)?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth", block: "start" })}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}

export default function PeriodicityQuestionBank() {
  const blocks = useMemo(() => parseMarkdown(RAW_MARKDOWN), []);

  return (
    <section className="qbankRoot" data-release={RELEASE}>
      <style>{`
        .qbankRoot { color: #eef3f8; max-width: 1120px; margin: 0 auto; }
        .qbankHero { border: 1px solid #2d4b69; border-radius: 18px; padding: 24px; margin-bottom: 22px; background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, rgba(95,212,234,.13), transparent 40%), linear-gradient(145deg, #112235, #0d1b2a); }
        .qbankKicker { margin: 0 0 8px; color: #e8b84b; font: 800 12px/1.2 ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace; letter-spacing: .12em; text-transform: uppercase; }
        .qbankHero h2 { margin: 0; font: 700 clamp(28px, 5vw, 46px)/1.05 Georgia, serif; }
        .qbankHero p { color: #bfd0de; line-height: 1.7; max-width: 820px; }
        .qbankJump { display: flex; gap: 9px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 15px; }
        .qbankJump button { border: 1px solid #355977; background: #14283b; color: #eef3f8; border-radius: 999px; padding: 9px 13px; font-weight: 750; cursor: pointer; }
        .qbankJump button:hover { border-color: #e8b84b; color: #e8b84b; }
        .qbankContent { display: grid; gap: 0; }
        .qbankContent h1, .qbankContent h2, .qbankContent h3, .qbankContent h4 { scroll-margin-top: 135px; }
        .qbankContent h1 { margin: 44px 0 18px; padding: 16px 18px; border: 1px solid #385b79; border-radius: 14px; background: linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(232,184,75,.13), rgba(95,212,234,.07)); font: 700 clamp(24px, 4vw, 36px)/1.2 Georgia, serif; color: #fff4cc; }
        .qbankContent h2 { margin: 34px 0 12px; font: 700 clamp(21px, 3vw, 29px)/1.25 Georgia, serif; color: #8adff0; border-bottom: 1px solid #294762; padding-bottom: 9px; }
        .qbankContent h3 { margin: 26px 0 9px; font: 800 18px/1.3 system-ui, sans-serif; color: #e8b84b; }
        .qbankContent h4 { margin: 20px 0 7px; color: #b9d4e8; }
        .qbankContent p { margin: 0 0 11px; padding: 13px 15px; border-left: 2px solid #2e526f; border-radius: 0 10px 10px 0; background: rgba(18,34,50,.65); color: #d9e5ee; line-height: 1.75; overflow-wrap: anywhere; }
        .qbankContent p strong { color: #fff2ba; }
        .qbankContent code { border: 1px solid #35536c; border-radius: 5px; padding: 1px 5px; background: #091521; color: #9de8f5; }
        .qbankMath { display: inline-block; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; overflow-x: auto; overflow-y: hidden; }
        .qbankRule { border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #294762; margin: 20px 0; }
        .qbankTableWrap { overflow-x: auto; border: 1px solid #2c4b65; border-radius: 13px; margin: 13px 0 20px; background: #0d1b29; }
        .qbankTable { width: 100%; min-width: 620px; border-collapse: collapse; }
        .qbankTable th { position: sticky; top: 0; background: #173149; color: #fff0b8; text-align: left; font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: .02em; }
        .qbankTable th, .qbankTable td { padding: 11px 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #29465e; border-right: 1px solid #223e55; vertical-align: top; line-height: 1.55; }
        .qbankTable tr:last-child td { border-bottom: 0; }
        .qbankTable th:last-child, .qbankTable td:last-child { border-right: 0; }
        @media (max-width: 650px) {
          .qbankHero { padding: 19px 15px; border-radius: 14px; }
          .qbankContent p { padding: 11px 12px; font-size: 14px; }
          .qbankContent h1 { padding: 13px 14px; }
        }
      `}</style>

      <div className="qbankHero">
        <p className="qbankKicker">99-question JEE Advanced drill bank</p>
        <h2>Periodicity Question Bank</h2>
        <p>
          Every question is presented before the consolidated answer key. Complete worked solutions follow at the end, preserving a clean examination-first sequence.
        </p>
        <div className="qbankJump" aria-label="Jump within question bank">
          <JumpButton target="part-i-questions">Questions</JumpButton>
          <JumpButton target="part-ii-consolidated-answer-key">Answer Key</JumpButton>
          <JumpButton target="part-iii-worked-solutions">Worked Solutions</JumpButton>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="qbankContent">
        {blocks.map((block, index) => {
          const key = `block-${index}`;
          if (block.kind === "rule") return <hr className="qbankRule" key={key} />;
          if (block.kind === "table") return <QuestionBankTable block={block} key={key} />;
          if (block.kind === "paragraph") return <p key={key}><InlineContent text={block.text} /></p>;

          const content = <InlineContent text={block.text} />;
          if (block.level === 1) return <h1 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h1>;
          if (block.level === 2) return <h2 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h2>;
          if (block.level === 3) return <h3 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h3>;
          return <h4 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h4>;
        })}
      </div>
    </section>
  );
}
